Rating: 3
This tastes very good and smells great. I doubled the recipe. I doubled both the peach filling and also the topping. Some of the changes I made were out of necessity. I was out of all purpose flour so I used self rising flour. I omitted the baking powder and salt because the self rising flour contians both of these. I used 2 tablespoons of corn starch in the doubled recipe,due to most reviews I read which suggested upping the amount of cornstarch. I used brown sugar in place of all the white after reading a lot of reviews suggesting brown tastes better. I left the skins on the peaches because I like a more rustic cobbler, I think the skin adds colour, texture and vitamins. My peaches were slightly underipe but this didn't hurt the tasty end results. I used a food processor to incorporate the butter {the way I would to make pastry} and I added powdered buttermilk to some 'skim plus' milk in place of the water into the food processor. {If using a processor be careful not to overprocess or your topping will be tough, not soft and appealing.} The resulting cobbler is fragrent, and the topping is crisp and almost breadcrumb like. I couldn't wait to taste it{I just made it a few minutes ago!} I had some while it was still very warm. I think it tastes very good. I will try making this again in the future useing the exact original unaltered ingredients in the original recipe. I don't think its necessary to add any spices such as cinimmon because the peaches really stand on thier own, but I don't think it would hurt at all if one did add some spice. I'ts just litterally a matter of personal 'taste'. I'll write another review when I made the unaltered recipe in the future and I'll tell which version I like better, the one with my changes, or the original unaltered one.

